259 Mar 12 00:33 BUILD_BRIEF.md\n-rw-r--r-- 1 ubuntu ubuntu  5467 Mar 12 00:33 README.md\n-rw-r--r-- 1 ubuntu ubuntu   952 Mar 12 00:33 api-spec.yaml\n-rw-r--r-- 1 ubuntu ubuntu    25 Mar 12 00:33 api-spec.yaml:Zone.Identifier\ndrwxr-xr-x 4 ubuntu ubuntu  4096 Mar 12 00:33 apps\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 ubuntu ubuntu  4096 Mar 12 00:33 docs\ndrwxr-xr-x 3 ubuntu ubuntu  4096 Mar 12 00:33 infra\n-rw-r--r-- 1 ubuntu ubuntu   497 Mar 12 00:33 package.json\n-rw-r--r-- 1 ubuntu ubuntu    25 Mar 12 00:33 package.json:Zone.Identifier\ndrwxr-xr-x 3 ubuntu ubuntu  4096 Mar 12 00:33 packages\n-rw-r--r-- 1 ubuntu ubuntu 51262 Mar 12 00:33 pnpm-lock.yaml\n-rw-r--r-- 1 ubuntu ubuntu   256 Mar 12 00:33 randm..md\n-rw-r--r-- 1 ubuntu ubuntu  6386 Mar 12 00:33 schema.sql\n-rw-r--r-- 1 ubuntu ubuntu    25 Mar 12 00:33 schema.sql:Zone.Identifier","cwd":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773275613406}}
{"type":"message","id":"a2778515","parentId":"8d514b7d","timestamp":"2026-03-12T00:33:35.950Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The repo is now cloned. Let me read the README to understand the project.","thinkingSignature":"1d04466533aa1fff903e68d4e9fc6b3e173e36f7fb49043297dbde507aaea691"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_lqun72gg83y4_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/studyclaw-starter-openclaw/README.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.5","usage":{"input":5669,"output":59,"cacheRead":13159,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":18887,"cost":{"input":0.0017006999999999999,"output":0.0000708,"cacheRead":0.00039476999999999996,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0021662699999999997}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773275613408}}
{"type":"message","id":"002320ea","parentId":"a2778515","timestamp":"2026-03-12T00:33:35.959Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_lqun72gg83y4_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# 🐾 StudyClaw SDK & Starter\n\n> **A low-stress academic command center for students.**\n\nStudyClaw is an open-source, mobile-first product designed to help students understand what matters now, what is coming next, and what actions will reduce pressure fastest. This starter repository gives you the building blocks to bring this vision to life with real-time AI context using **OpenClaw**.\n\n---\n\n## 🎯 Product Vision & Core Rules\n\nOur core philosophy is simple: **Reduce student stress**. These non-negotiable rules override feature convenience and must drive all implementation decisions:\n\n1. **Clarity Over Density:** Show the next best action first. Every screen must reduce stress.\n2. **Immediate Priorities:** The home dashboard must quickly highlight deadlines, overdue work, and upcoming exams.\n3. **Grounded AI Assistant:** The AI must connect to real app data (courses, files, deadlines) and isn't isolated.\n4. **Proactive Automation:** Assignments, exams, and uploaded materials drive suggestions automatically.\n5. **Smart Reminders:** Notifications must be school-contextual.\n6. **Immediate Value:** The product must be helpful *before* the user even types a single prompt.\n\n---\n\n## 🏗️ Tech Stack & Architecture\n\nThe repository currently serves as a mono-repo starter.\n\n- **Frontend (`apps/web`)**: Next.js React prototype.\n- **Backend (`apps/api`)**: Express + TypeScript API.\n- **Database (`schema.sql`)**: PostgreSQL with `pgcrypto` & `citext`.\n- **AI Integration**: OpenClaw Gateway.\n\n---\n\n## 🚀 Getting Started (Local Development)\n\n### Prerequisites\n- **Node.js**: v20 or newer\n- **pnpm**: v9 or newer\n- **PostgreSQL**: Local database instance running\n\n### 1. Database Setup\nProvision a local PostgreSQL database and apply the initial schema:\n\n```bash\ncreatedb studyclaw_dev\npsql studyclaw_dev < schema.sql\n```\n\n### 2. Install Dependencies\nRun this at the root of the repository:\n```bash\npnpm install\n```\n\n### 3. Environment Variables\nCreate a `.env` file in `apps/api` (or copy `.env.example`). You can use the values from your configuration or the test credentials provided in the repository:\n\n```ini\nDATABASE_URL=\"postgres://postgres:postgres@localhost:5432/studyclaw\"\nOPENCLAW_BASE_URL=\"https://3.144.253.238\"\nOPENCLAW_GATEWAY_TOKEN=\"cea9b28f983583ff00bd47697a7ed20f833dd4e39cbb2099\"\nNODE_TLS_REJECT_UNAUTHORIZED=0\nPORT=4000\n```\n> ⚠️ **Warning:** The `OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_TOKEN` must never be exposed to the frontend. If it is, rotate it immediately before deploying to production.\n\n### 4. Start the Application\nYou can run the frontend and backend concurrently in separate terminal windows.\n\n**Start the Backend (API):**\n```bash\npnpm dev:api\n```\n\n**Start the Frontend (Web):**\n```bash\npnpm dev:web\n```\n\nVisit [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000) to view the priority-first UI, test the onboarding, and explore chat flows.\n\n---\n\n## 🌍 Production Deployment (VPS)\n\nReady to test on a remote server? Use a Linux VPS (Ubuntu 24.04+ recommended) and follow these steps:\n\n1. **System Prep:** Install Node 20+, `pnpm`, Postgres, and `nginx` (to reverse-proxy).\n2. **Clone & Install:** Clone the repository and run `pnpm install`.\n3. **Database Initialization:** Create `studyclaw_prod` and apply `schema.sql`.\n4. **Environment Variables:** Set up your `.env` securely outside the repo with production values and set `NODE_ENV=production`.\n5. **Start API:** Start the backend with a process manager like `pm2` or a `systemd` service:\n   ```bash\n   NODE_ENV=production pnpm dev:api\n   ```\n6. **Start Web Application:** Build and start the Next.js frontend:\n   ```bash\n   pnpm --filter apps/web build\n   pnpm --filter apps/web start\n   ```\n7. **Reverse Proxy & Domain:** Use `infra/nginx/studyclaw-api.conf` as a starting template to proxy `/api` requests to the backend while serving the Next.js frontend. Link it with your DNS and verify everything on port 80/443.\n\n---\n\n## 🗺️ Roadmap & Immediate Priorities\n\n### Technical Gap vs Build Brief\n- **Platform Strategy:** We're currently using a Next.js web client. **Sprint 1** will decide whether to replace `apps/web` with an Expo mobile app natively or build the new Expo app alongside it.\n- **Schema & API Progress:** Our `schema.sql` covers basic entities (users, subjects, chat roles, and reminders). The immediate next step is expanding CRUD endpoints for assignments, exams, and planner states to fulfill the low-stress product mandate.\n\n### Delivery Sprints\n\n* **Sprint 1 (Foundations):** Expo scaffold (or Next.js refinement), Auth screens, Bottom tab navigation, Onboarding flow, PostgreSQL schema setup, Course/Task CRUD.\n* **Sprint 2 (Core Loop):** Dashboard UI, Upcoming assignments, Reminder creation, Push notifications, Chat screen.\n* **Sprint 3 (Intelligence):** File upload, Syllabus parser, Study planner, Grade estimator.\n* **Sprint 4 (Polish):** UI polish, Edge cases, Analytics, Mobile Android build & internal testing.\n\n### Immediate Developer Action Items\n1. Initialize the Postgres DB and run the provided `schema.sql`.\n2. Replace the dummy `x-user-id` auth middleware across the app with real JWT authentication.\n3. Start the API locally and test `/api/chat/send` for users that have completed onboarding.\n4. Scale up features by adding OCR, transcription, and object storage for uploaded study materials.\n\n---\n\n> 📖 **Need deeper context?** Please consult the `BUILD_BRIEF.md` for our full product contract, vision principles, and complete context.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773275615957}}
